# UI Accessibility Rules

## Context

- Apply when implementing interactive elements, color feedback, or touch targets.
- Ensures UI is accessible while maintaining game-like feel.
- Accessibility must not compromise the neo-brutalist visual style.

## Requirements

### Touch Targets

- Minimum tap target: `44px` (iOS/Android standard).
- Answer buttons: Use `56px` minimum height (exceeds requirement).
- HUD elements: Ensure `44px` minimum touch area.
- Bottom dock buttons: `48–56px` square (exceeds requirement).

### Color Contrast

- Ink outline ensures high contrast (black on white/colored backgrounds).
- Maintain WCAG AA contrast ratios for text on colored backgrounds.
- Test green (`#29F724`) and red (`#FE3F3B`) text on white/ink backgrounds.

### Non-Color Feedback

- Don't rely on color alone for correctness feedback.
- Add icon (checkmark/X) or text ("Correct"/"Incorrect") alongside color changes.
- Use both visual (color) and textual/iconographic feedback.

### Focus States

- Provide visible focus indicators for keyboard navigation.
- Use thick outline (2–3px) in accent color (cyan or yellow) for focus.
- Maintain game-like aesthetic (not default browser outline).

### Screen Reader Support

- Use semantic HTML (`<button>`, `<nav>`, etc.).
- Provide `aria-label` for icon-only buttons.
- Announce correctness feedback with `aria-live` regions.
- Label form inputs and interactive elements properly.

### Reduced Motion

- Respect `prefers-reduced-motion` media query.
- Disable animations for users who prefer reduced motion.
- Maintain functionality without animations.

## Examples

<example>
  Valid answer button with accessibility:
  
  ```tsx
  <button
    className="h-14 w-full border-4 border-ink rounded-[18px] shadow-sticker-sm font-bold"
    aria-label={`Answer option: ${answerText}`}
    aria-pressed={isSelected}
  >
    {isSelected && <span className="sr-only">Selected</span>}
    {answerText}
  </button>
  ```
</example>

<example type="invalid">
  Invalid: Button below minimum touch target:
  
  ```tsx
  <button className="h-10 w-full"> {/* Too small */}
    {answerText}
  </button>
  ```
</example>

<example>
  Valid correctness feedback with non-color indicator:
  
  ```tsx
  {isCorrect && (
    <div className="flex items-center gap-2 text-green">
      <CheckIcon aria-hidden="true" />
      <span>Correct!</span>
    </div>
  )}
  ```
</example>

<example type="invalid">
  Invalid: Color-only feedback:
  
  ```tsx
  <div className={isCorrect ? 'text-green' : 'text-red'}>
    {/* No icon or text, relies only on color */}
  </div>
  ```
</example>

<example>
  Valid focus state:
  
  ```css
  .answer-button:focus-visible {
    outline: 3px solid var(--cyanA);
    outline-offset: 2px;
  }
  ```
</example>
